The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Business Briefs

 Dubai, April 14: India and Saudi Arabia will sign a bilateral investment protection agreement before the expected visit of Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah by the year-end, finance minister P. Chidambaram has said. He also assured Saudi businessmen that even without the agreement, their investments in India would be safe. ?Even in the absence of such an agreement, no investment can be expropriated in India. The rule of law guarantees that all your investments are absolutely safe,? he told a meeting organised at the Jeddah Chamber of Commerce and Industry.

 Tokyo, April 14: Japan and India today took a step towards a possible free-trade deal during a meeting between commerce minister Kamal Nath and Japanese Prime Minister Junichiro Koizumi. 

 New Delhi, April 14: Trade unions in the coal sector today threatened to call a strike if their demands, mainly full neutralisation of dearness allowance, are not met.

 Frankfurt, April 14: Deutsche Lufthansa AG will increase ticket surcharges by 59 per cent to help cover the higher cost of fuel. Lufthansa will raise fuel surcharges to 27 euros from 17 euros to long-distance destinations from April 25.

 Mumbai, April 14: Ranbaxy Laboratories has entered into a collaborative agreement with the Pune-based National Chemical Laboratories and the department of science amp; technology for drug discovery.




